As a transplant from the south, I'm always on the hunt for some good soul food and I'm happy to report that Brenda's got it! The beignets are a classic go-to appetizer order. Even though I don't like to start off a savory meal with sweets, who can really say no to some fried dough? The beignets at Brenda's are fried to perfection, with a light and fluffy inside. My favorites are definitely the original or the crawfish. The crawfish beignets have a bit of spice, but the savory filling goes really well with the texture of the beignet itself. I'm also a huge fan of grits and I'm glad that Brenda's does 'em right! The crispy pork belly with grits was amazing, as were the beef grillades with grits. Overall, I'd say Brenda's is worth the wait if you've got the time for it. The food is so rich and indulgent, and it's the perfect way to start a Saturday or Sunday!

It was a lot of food and we got stuffed as a result. For the beignet, I like the crawfish one the best. The other three are all sweet flavor. They taste like normal pastry (more like donuts) for me. But the crawfish is something I've never tried before and it's good! I had shrimp & grits as my entree and I love it. At first I thought it might be too heavy with all the cheese. But it turned out that the tomato, bacon and shrimp mixed so well with it. I finished the whole bowl without feeling overwhelmed. It's definitely not light either of course. :p I tried some hangtown fry's egg with oyster. It's good too! It's kind of like omelette but not in a brunch style. My friend said the fried chicken in BFC has very crispy skin, but very juicy meat inside with good texture. He liked it! As for the crispy pork belly, I am not a big fan of it. Although my friends think it is special and worth of trying, I think it is too dry and hard to bite. I like soft pork belly better.

Brenda's probably has one of the busiest and longest lines during weekend brunch times in SF and after eating here twice already, although it is good, I don't really think it's worth the long wait or worth the hype. I've tried many of their dishes and I think my favorites would have to be the crawfish beignets, chocolate beignets, and any of their grits dishes. The crawfish beignet filling has a nice little cajun spice to it and it's always very satisfying seeing the filling ooze out of the beignets (lol). They're also fried perfectly every time, not too burnt or under cooked. Their grits are also one of their best dishes imo, especially the pork belly one. The spice of the pork belly compliments the cheesy ooey gooey-ness of the grits so well! Now for some of their not-as-great dishes: any of the benedicts tbh are kind of a let down. The fried chicken benedict was pretty bland and the fried chicken wasn't crispy at all; kinda tasted like they pre make the chicken so it's been out a while. The pulled pork wasn't anything special; the bbq sauce on the pulled pork just tasted like a sauce that I can buy off the shelf of a grocery store. Overall, this place is decent but I wouldn't wait more than 30 minutes to get a table here.

My co-workers took me here for lunch because we've been craving fried chicken. Don't get me wrong, it's good food but to wait an hour+ during lunch time? It's not that good. We ordered the Beignet Flight, several pieces of BFC, cole slaw, fries and red beans & rice. BFC - Delicious fried chicken. Fried chicken that you could not compare to fast food. This is worthy of a sit-down. The skin was crispy with a good coat that wasn't too thick. The meat inside was juicy and tender. Each piece was cook to perfection! I thoroughly enjoyed this. The one suggestion I would recommend is to put some oil-absorbing paper between the chicken and plate. The chicken was literally sitting in a puddle of oil/grease. I blotted down my chicken each time with a napkin to take off the excess fat. Cole Slaw - Good cole slaw, nothing special. Fries - Good fries, they were different from your usual fries because they were battered and then fried. Adding to the extra good pool of comfort food. Red beans & rice - Good, it came with sausages as well. Overall, it is good food, but I don't get how it was worth the wait time. Personally, I won't be back just due to the long wait.

    11/19/2018

    2 photos

    My co-workers took me here for lunch because we've been craving fried chicken. The wait was about 45 minutes and personally, I don't think it's worth it nor do I understand why people are willing to wait hours on end to eat here. Don't get me wrong, it's good food but to wait an hour+ during lunch time? It's not that good.

    We ordered the Beignet Flight, several pieces of BFC, cole slaw, fries and red beans & rice.

    Beignet Flight - Overall, good beignets but I still don't get what's so special about a beignet. It's just fried dough with powdered sugar on top. The only one that stood out to me was the Crawfish beignet. Now that, I could order a plate of and consume at $12.00. The crawfish was juicy and not overpowered by the spices and cheese.

    BFC - Delicious fried chicken. Fried chicken that you could not compare to fast food. This is worthy of a sit-down. The skin was crispy with a good coat that wasn't too thick. The meat inside was juicy and tender. Each piece was cook to perfection! I thoroughly enjoyed this. The one suggestion I would recommend is to put some oil-absorbing paper between the chicken and plate. The chicken was literally sitting in a puddle of oil/grease. I blotted down my chicken each time with a napkin to take off the excess fat.

    Cole Slaw - Good cole slaw, nothing special.

    Fries - Good fries, they were different from your usual fries because they were battered and then fried. Adding to the extra good pool of comfort food.

    Red beans & rice - Good, it came with sausages as well.

    Overall, it is good food, but I don't get how it was worth the wait time. Personally, I won't be back just due to the long wait.
